\par 
\par Monotonous days. The three-man Harkonnen patrol cruised over the 
\par golden swells of dunes along a thousand-kilometer flight path. In the 
\par unrelenting desert landscape, even a puff of dust caused excitement. 
\par 
\par The troopers flew their armored ornithopter in a long circle, skirting 
\par mountains, then curving south over great pans and flatlands. Glossu 
\par Rabban, the Baron's nephew and temporary governor of Arrakis, had 
\par ordered them to fly regularly, to be seen-to show the squalid 
\par settlements that Harkonnens were watching. Always. 
\par 
\par Kiel, the sidegunner, considered the assignment a license to hunt any 
\par Fremen found wandering near legitimate spice-harvesting operations. 
\par What made those dirty wanderers think they could trespass on 
\par Harkonnen lands without permission from the district office in 
\par Carthag? But few Fremen were ever caught abroad in daylight, and the 
\par task had grown dull. 
\par 
\par Garan flew the 'thopter, rising up and dipping down to catch thermals, 
\par as if operating an amusement ride. He maintained a stoic expression, 
\par though occasionally a grin stole across his lips as the craft bucked and 
\par jostled in rough air. As they completed their fifth day on patrol, he 
\par continued to mark discrepancies on topographical maps, muttering in 
\par disgust each time he found another mistake. These were the worst 
\par charts he had ever used. 
\par 
\par In the back passenger compartment sat Josten, recently transferred from 
\par Giedi Prime. Accustomed to industrial facilities, gray skies, and dirty 
\par buildings, Josten gazed out over the sandy wastelands, studying 
\par hypnotic dune patterns. He spotted the knot of dust off to the south, 
\par deep in the open Funeral Plain. "What's that? Spice-harvesting 
\par operation?" 
\par 
\par "Not a chance," the sidegunner Kiel said. "Harvesters shoot a plume 
\par like a cone into the air, straight and thin." 
\par 
\par "Too low for a dust devil. Too small." With a shrug, Garan jerked the 
\par 'thopter controls and soared toward the low, reddish-brown cloud. 
\par "Let's take a look." After so many tedious days, they would have gone 
\par out of their way to investigate a large rock sticking out of the sand... 
\par 
\par When they reached the site, they found no tracks, no machinery, no 
\par sign of human presence-and yet acres of desert looked devastated. A 
\par mottled rust color stained the sands a darker ochre, as if blood from a 
\par wound had dried in the hot sun. 
\par 
\par "Looks like somebody dropped a bomb here," Kiel said. 
\par 
\par "Could be the aftermath of a spice blow," Garan suggested. "I'll set 
\par down for a closer look." 
\par 
\par As the 'thopter settled onto the churned sands, Kiel popped open the 
\par hatch. The temperature-controlled atmosphere hissed out, replaced by a 
\par wave of heat. He coughed dust. 
\par 
\par Garan leaned over from the cockpit and sniffed hard. "Smell it." The 
\par odor of burnt cinnamon struck his nostrils. "Spice blow for sure." 
\par 
\par Josten squeezed past Kiel and dropped onto the soft ground. Amazed, 
\par he bent down, picked up a handful of ochre sand and touched it to his 
\par lips. "Can we scoop up some fresh spice and take it back? Must be 
\par worth a fortune." 
\par 
\par Kiel had been thinking the same thing, but now he turned to the 
\par newcomer with scorn. "We don't have the processing equipment. You 
\par need to separate it from the sand, and you can't do that with your 
\par fingers." 
\par 
\par Garan spoke in a quieter, but firmer voice. "If you went back to 
\par Carthag and tried to sell raw product to a street vendor you'd be hauled 
\par in front of Governor Rabban-or worse yet, have to explain to Count 
\par Fenring how some of the Emperor's spice ended up in a patrolman's 
\par pockets." 
\par 
\par As the troopers tromped out to the ragged pit at the center of the 
\par dissipating dust cloud, Josten glanced around. "Is it safe for us to be 
\par here? Don't the big worms go to spice?" 
\par 
\par "Afraid, kid?" Kiel asked. 
\par 
\par "Let's throw him to a worm if we see one," Garan suggested. "It'll give 
\par us time to get away." 
\par 
\par Kiel saw movement in the sandy excavation, shapes squirming, buried 
\par things that tunneled and burrowed, like maggots in rotten meat. Josten 
\par opened his mouth to say something, then clamped it shut again. 
\par 
\par A whiplike creature emerged from the sand, two meters long with 
\par fleshy segmented skin. It was the size of a large snake, its mouth an 
\par open circle glittering with needle-sharp teeth that lined its throat. 
\par 
\par "A sandworm!" Josten said. 
\par 
\par "Only a runt," Kiel scoffed. 
\par 
\par "Newborn-do you think?" Garan asked. 
\par 
\par The worm waved its eyeless head from side to side. Other slithering 
\par creatures, a nest of them, squirmed about as if they'd been spawned in 
\par the explosion. 
\par 
\par "Where in the hells did they come from?" Kiel asked. 
\par 
\par "Wasn't in my briefing," Garan said. 
\par 
\par "Can we ... catch one?" Josten asked. 
\par 
\par Kiel stopped himself from making a rude rejoinder, realizing that the 
\par young recruit did have a good idea. "Come on!" He charged forward 
\par into the churned sand. 
\par 
\par The worm sensed the movement and reared back, uncertain whether to 
\par attack or flee. Then it arced like a sea serpent and plunged into the 
\par sand, wriggling and burrowing. 
\par 
\par Josten sprinted ahead and dove face-first to grasp the segmented body 
\par three quarters of the way to its end. "It's so strong!" Following him, the 
\par sidegunner jumped down and grabbed the thrashing tail. 
\par 
\par The worm tried to tug away, but Garan reached the front, where he dug 
\par into the sand and grabbed behind its head with a stranglehold. All three 
\par troopers wrestled and pulled. "Get it!" The small worm thrashed like an 
\par eel on an electric plate. 
\par 
\par Other sandworms on the far side of the pit rose like a strange forest of 
\par periscopes sprouting from the sea of dunes, round mouths like black os 
\par turned toward the men. For an icy moment, Kiel feared they might 
\par attack like a swarm of marrow leeches, but the immature worms darted 
\par away and disappeared underground. 
\par 
\par Garan and Kiel hauled their captive out of the sand and dragged it 
\par toward the ornithopter. As a Harkonnen patrol, they had all the 
\par equipment necessary to arrest criminals, including old-fashioned 
\par devices for trussing a captive like a herd animal. "Josten, go get the 
\par binding cords in our apprehension kit," the pilot said. 
\par 
\par The new recruit came running back with the cords, fashioning a loop 
\par which he slipped over the worm's head and cinched tight. Garan 
\par released his hold on the rubbery skin and grabbed the rope, tugging 
\par while Josten slipped a second cord lower on the body. 
\par 
\par "What are we going to do with it?" Josten asked. 
\par 
\par Once, early in his assignment on Arrakis, Kiel had joined Rabban on an 
\par abortive worm hunt. They had taken a Fremen guide, well-armed 
\par troops, even a Planetologist. Using the Fremen guide as bait, they had 
\par lured one of the enormous sandworms and killed it with explosives. But 
\par before Rabban could take his trophy, the beast had dissolved, sloughing 
\par into amoeba creatures that fell to the sand, leaving nothing but a 
\par cartilaginous skeleton and loose crystal teeth. Rabban had been furious. 
\par 
\par Kiel's stomach knotted. The Baron's nephew might consider it an insult 
\par that three simple patrolmen could capture a worm, when he'd been 
\par unable to do so himself. "We'd better drown it." 
\par 
\par "Drown it?" Josten said. "What for? And why would I want to waste 
\par my water ration to do that?" 
\par 
\par Garan stopped as if struck by a thunderbolt. "I've heard the Fremen do 
\par it. If you drown a baby worm, they say it spits out some kind of drug or 
\par poison. It's very rare." 
\par 
\par Kiel nodded. "Oh, yeah. The desert people use it in their religious 
\par rituals. It makes everybody go crazy, wild orgies and everything." 
\par 
\par "But ... we've only got two literjons of water in the compartment," 
\par Josten said, still nervous. 
\par 
\par "Then we only use one. I know where we can refill it, anyway." The 
\par pilot and his sidegunner exchanged glances. They had patrolled 
\par together long enough that they'd both thought of the same thing. 
\par 
\par As if understanding its fate, the worm bucked and thrashed even more, 
\par but it was already growing weaker. 
\par 
\par "Once we get the drug," Kiel said, "let's have some fun." 
\par 
