\par At night, with the patrol 'thopter running in stealth mode, they flew 
\par over the razor-edged mountains, approaching from behind a ridge and 
\par landing on a rough mesa above the squalid village of Bilar Camp. The 
\par villagers lived in hollowed-out caves and aboveground structures that 
\par extended out to the flats. Windmills generated power; supply bins 
\par glittered with tiny lights that attracted a few moths and the bats that fed 
\par on them.
\par  
\par Unlike the nomadic Fremen, these villagers were slightly more 
\par civilized but also more downtrodden: men who worked as desert guides 
\par and joined spice-harvesting crews. They had forgotten how to survive 
\par on their world without becoming parasites upon the planetary 
\par governors. 
\par 
\par On an earlier patrol, Kiel and Garan had discovered a camouflaged 
\par cistern on the mesa, a treasure trove of water. Kiel didn't know where 
\par the villagers had gotten so much moisture; most likely, they had 
\par committed fraud, inflating their census numbers so that Harkonnen 
\par generosity provided more than they deserved. 
\par 
\par The people of Bilar Camp covered the cistern with rock so that it 
\par looked like a natural protrusion, but the villagers placed no guards 
\par around their illegal stockpile. For some reason desert culture forbade 
\par thievery even more than murder; they trusted the safety of their 
\par possessions from bandits or thieves of the night. 
\par 
\par Of course, the Harkonnen troopers had no intention of stealing the 
\par water-that is, no more than enough to refill their own supply 
\par containers. 
\par 
\par Dutifully, Josten trotted along with their sloshing container, which held 
\par the thick, noxious substance exuded by the drowned worm after it had 
\par stopped thrashing and bucking inside the container. Awed and nervous 
\par about what they'd done, they dumped the flaccid carcass near the 
\par perimeter of the spice blow and then taken off with the drug. 
\par 
\par Garan operated the Bilar cistern's cleverly concealed spigot and refilled 
\par one of their empty containers. No sense in letting all the water go to 
\par waste just for a practical joke on the villagers. 
\par 
\par "Do you know what this drug will do to them?" Josten asked. 
\par 
\par Garan shook his head. "I've heard plenty of crazy stories." 
\par 
\par "Maybe we should make the kid try it first," the sidegunner said. 
\par 
\par Josten backed away, raising his hands. 
\par 
\par Kiel took the container of worm bile and upended it into the cistern. 
\par The villagers would certainly have a surprise next time they all drank 
\par from their illegal water hoard. "Serves them right." 
\par 
\par Garan looked at the contaminated cistern again. "I bet they tear off their 
\par clothes and dance naked in the streets, squawking like dinfowl." 
\par 
\par "Let's stay here and watch the fun for ourselves," Kiel said. 
\par 
\par Garan frowned. "Do you want to be the one to explain to Rabban why 
\par we're late returning from patrol?" 
\par 
\par "Let's go," Kiel answered quickly. 
\par 
\par As the worm-poison infused the cistern, the Harkonnen troopers 
\par hurried back to their ornithopter, reluctantly content to let the villagers 
\par discover the prank for themselves. 
