\par It is said that the Fremen has no conscience, having lost it in a burning 
\par desire for revenge. This is foolish. Only the rawest primitive and the 
\par sociopath have no conscience. The Fremen possesses a highly evolved 
\par world view centered on the welfare of his people. His sense of 
\par belonging to the community is almost stronger than his sense of self. It 
\par is only to outsiders that these desert-dwellers seem brutish ... just as 
\par outsiders appear to them. 
\par 
\par -Pardot Kynes, The People of Arrakis
\par 
\par 
\par "Luxury is for the noble-born, Liet," Pardot Kynes, Imperial 
\par Planetologist to Arrakis, said to his son as the groundcar trundled 
\par across the uneven ground. "On this planet you must instantly become 
\par aware of your own surroundings, and remain alert at all times. If you 
\par fail to learn this lesson, you won't live long." 
\par 
\par As Kynes operated the simple controls, he gestured toward the buttery 
\par morning light that melted across the stark dunes. "There are rewards 
\par here, too." Kynes exhaled a long breath between his hard chapped lips. 
\par 
\par Young Liet stared out the scratched windowplaz. Unlike his father, 
\par who reeled off whatever random thoughts occurred to him, making 
\par pronouncements that the Fremen heeded as if they were weighty 
\par spiritual matters, Liet preferred silence. He narrowed his eyes to study 
\par the landscape, searching for any small thing out of its place. Always 
\par alert. 
\par 
\par On such a harsh planet, one had to develop stored perceptions, each of 
\par them linked to every moment of survival. Though his father was much 
\par older, Liet wasn't certain the Planetologist understood as much as he 
\par himself did. The mind of Pardot Kynes contained powerful concepts, 
\par but the older man experienced them only as esoteric data. He didn't 
\par understand the desert in his heart or in his soul... 
\par 
\par For years, Kynes had lived among the Fremen. It was said that Emperor 
\par Shaddam IV had little interest in his activities, and since Kynes asked 
\par for no funding and few supplies, the Emperor and the Harkonnens left 
\par him alone. With each passing year he slipped farther from attention. 
\par Shaddam and his advisors had stopped expecting any grand revelations 
\par from the Planetologist's periodic reports. 
\par 
\par This suited Pardot Kynes, and his son as well. 
\par 
\par In his wanderings, Kynes often made trips to outlying villages where 
\par the people of the pan and graben scratched out squalid lives. True 
\par Fremen rarely mixed with the townspeople, and viewed them with 
\par veiled contempt for being too soft, too civilized. Liet would never have 
\par lived in those pathetic settlements for all the solaris in the Imperium. 
\par But still, Pardot visited them. 
\par 
\par Eschewing roads and commonly traveled paths, they rode in the 
\par groundcar, checking meteorological stations and collecting data, though 
\par Pardot's troops of devoted Fremen would gladly have done this menial 
\par work for their "Umma," or prophet. 
\par 
\par Liet-Kynes's features echoed many of his father's, though with a leaner 
\par face and the close-set eyes of his Fremen mother. He had pale hair, and 
\par his chin was still smooth, though later he would likely grow a beard 
\par similar to the great Planetologist's. Liet's eyes had the deep blue of 
\par spice addiction, since every meal and breath of air was laced with 
\par melange. 
\par 
\par Liet heard a sharp intake of breath from his father as they passed the 
\par jagged elbow of a canyon where camouflaged catchtraps directed 
\par moisture to plantings of rabbitbush and poverty grasses. "See? It's 
\par taking on a life of its own. We'll 'cycle' the planet through prairie phase 
\par into forest over several generations. The sand has a high salt content, 
\par indicating old oceans, and the spice itself is alkaline." He chuckled. 
\par "People in the Imperium would be horrified that we'd use spice 
\par byproducts for something as menial as fertilizer." He smiled at his son. 
\par "But we know the value of such things, eh? If we break down the spice, 
\par we can set up protein digestion. Even now, if we flew high enough, we 
\par could spot patches of green where matted plant growth holds the dune 
\par faces in place." 
\par 
\par The young man sighed. His father was a great man with magnificent 
\par dreams for Dune-and yet Kynes was so focused on one thing that he 
\par failed to see the universe around him. Liet knew that if any Harkonnen 
\par patrols found the plantings, they would destroy them and punish the 
\par Fremen. 
\par 
\par Though only twelve, Liet regularly went out on guerrilla raids with his 
\par Fremen brothers and had already killed Harkonnens. For more than a 
\par year, he and his friends-led by the brash Stilgar-had struck targets 
\par that others refused to consider. Only a week before, Liet's companions 
\par had blown up a dozen patrol 'thopters at a supply post. Unfortunately, 
\par the stupid Harkonnen troops had taken their revenge against poor 
\par villagers, seeing no difference between settled folk and the will-o'-the-
\par sand Fremen. 
\par 
\par He hadn't told his father about his guerrilla activities, since the elder 
\par Kynes wouldn't understand the necessity. Premeditated violence, for 
\par whatever reason, was a foreign concept to the Planetologist. But Liet 
\par would do what needed to be done. 
\par 
\par Now, the groundcar approached a village tucked into the rocky 
\par foothills; it was called Bilar Camp on their terrain maps. Pardot 
\par continued to talk about melange and its peculiar properties. "They 
\par found spice too soon on Arrakis. It deflected scientific inquiry. It was 
\par so useful right from the outset that no one bothered to probe its 
\par mysteries." 
\par 
\par Liet turned to look at him. "I thought that was why you were assigned 
\par here in the first place-to understand the spice." 
\par 
\par "Yes ... but we have more important work to do. I still report back to 
\par the Imperium often enough to convince them I'm working at my job ... 
\par though not very successfully." Talking about the first time he'd been to 
\par this region, he drove toward a cluster of dirty buildings the color of 
\par sand and dust. 
\par 
\par The groundcar jounced over a rough rock, but Liet ignored it and stared 
\par ahead at the village, squinting his eyes in the harsh light of the desert 
\par morning. The morning air held the fragility of fine crystal. 
\par "Something's wrong," he said, interrupting his father. 
\par 
\par Kynes continued talking for a few seconds and then brought the vehicle 
\par to a stop. "What's that?" 
\par 
\par "Something is wrong." Liet pointed ahead at the village. 
\par 
\par Kynes shaded his eyes against the glare. "I don't see anything." 
\par 
\par "Still ... let us proceed with caution." 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par \'b7 \'b7 \'b7 \'b7 \'b7  
\par 
\par 
\par In the center of the village, they encountered a festival of horrors. 
\par 
\par The noise was appalling, as was the smell. Bodies lay sprawled on the 
\par ground like squashed insects, arms and legs stiffened at odd angles, 
\par while tortured survivors wandered about as if insane, shrieking and 
\par snarling like animals. They had ripped hair out of their heads in bloody 
\par clumps. Some used long fingernails to claw the eyes out of their faces, 
\par then held the scooped eyeballs in their palms; blind, they staggered 
\par against the tan walls of dwellings, leaving wet crimson smears. 
\par 
\par Even the dead ones did not look at peace. 
\par 
\par "By Shai-Hulud!" Liet whispered under his breath, while his father let 
\par out a louder curse in common Imperial Galach. 
\par 
\par One man with torn eye sockets like bloody extra mouths above his 
\par cheekbones collided with a crawling woman; both victims flew into a 
\par rage and ripped at each other's skin with bare hands, biting and spitting 
\par and screaming. There were muddy spots on the street, overturned 
\par containers of water. 
\par 
\par Some buildings were locked and shuttered, barricaded against the 
\par crazed wretches outside who pounded on the walls, wailing wordlessly 
\par to get in. On an upper floor Liet saw a woman's terrified face at the 
\par dust-streaked windowplaz. Others hid, somehow unaffected by the 
\par murderous insanity. 
\par 
\par "We must help these people, Father." Liet leaped out of the sealed 
\par groundcar before his father had brought it to a complete stop. "Bring 
\par your weapons. We may need to defend ourselves." 
\par 
\par They carried old maula pistols as well as knives. His father, though a 
\par scientist at heart, was also a good fighter-a skill he reserved for 
\par defending his vision for Arrakis. The legend was told of how he had 
\par slain several Harkonnen bravos who'd been attempting to kill three 
\par young Fremen. Those rescued Fremen were now his most loyal 
\par lieutenants, Stilgar, Turok, and Ommun. But Pardot Kynes had never 
\par fought against anything like this... 
\par 
\par The maddened villagers noticed them and moaned. They began to 
\par move forward. 
\par 
\par "Don't kill them unless you must," Kynes said, amazed at how quickly 
\par his son had armed himself with a crysknife and maula pistol. "Watch 
\par yourself." 
\par 
\par Liet ventured into the street. What struck him first was the terrible 
\par stink, as if the foul breath of a dying leper had been captured in a bottle 
\par and slowly released. 
\par 
\par Staring in disbelief, Pardot stepped farther from the groundcar. He saw 
\par no lasgun burn marks in the village, no chip scars from projectile 
\par weapons, nothing that would have indicated an overt Harkonnen attack. 
\par Was it a disease? If so, it might be contagious. If a plague or some kind 
\par of communicable insanity was at work here, he could not let the 
\par Fremen take these bodies for the deathstills. 
\par 
\par Liet moved forward. "Fremen would attribute this to demons." 
\par 
\par Two of the bloody-faced victims let out demonic shrieks and rushed 
\par toward them, their fingers outstretched like eagle claws, their mouths 
\par open like bottomless pits. Liet pointed the maula pistol, closed his eyes 
